Annie has an announcement.

67
00:06:39,399 --> 00:06:44,695
Oh... Walter and I are engaged.

68
00:06:44,863 --> 00:06:45,988
[SCREAMING]

69
00:06:49,618 --> 00:06:53,037
Thank you. Thank you.

70
00:06:53,205 --> 00:06:55,456
Mum knew.
Dad, Mum knew.

71
00:06:55,624 --> 00:06:57,333
I don't see a ring, Annie.

72
00:06:58,585 --> 00:07:00,377
Congratulations, Walter.

73
00:07:00,545 --> 00:07:02,880
[SNEEZING]

74
00:07:03,048 --> 00:07:05,007
Bless you. Bless you!

75
00:07:06,635 --> 00:07:10,137
CLIFF: Are you all right?
It's nothing. It's nothing.

76
00:07:10,305 --> 00:07:11,680
Maybe it's the flowers.

77
00:07:11,848 --> 00:07:12,890
BARBARA:
We'll move them.

78
00:07:13,058 --> 00:07:17,520
No, don't touch them!
I feel terrible, sneezing at
a time like this.

79
00:07:17,687 --> 00:07:19,396
This is a very important moment for me.

80
00:07:19,564 --> 00:07:21,440
He's allergic to everything,
don't worry about him.

81
00:07:21,608 --> 00:07:24,360
Bees.
I'm allergic to bees.

82
00:07:24,528 --> 00:07:27,321
Harold is allergic to every type of bee.

83
00:07:27,489 --> 00:07:31,033
We always have to
carry a hypodermic of
adrenalin wherever we go.

84
00:07:31,201 --> 00:07:33,619
If he eats even one tiny piece of a nut...

85
00:07:33,787 --> 00:07:37,665
My head swells up
like a watermelon
and I drop dead.

86
00:07:37,833 --> 00:07:39,667
IRENE:
It's the same with him and bees.

87
00:07:39,835 --> 00:07:42,044
Your mother and I had salmon at our wedding.

88
00:07:42,212 --> 00:07:44,880
I really think
a wedding without
cold salmon is...

89
00:07:45,048 --> 00:07:48,134
I'm not allergic to salmon.
Oh, he's not allergic...

90
00:07:48,301 --> 00:07:50,678
I don't think.
But you never know.

91
00:07:50,846 --> 00:07:54,348
You never know.
Harold wasn't always allergic to bees.

92
00:07:54,516 --> 00:07:55,724
BARBARA: Oh, honey,
what a shame.

93
00:07:55,892 --> 00:07:58,060
We had some champagne.
What did we use it for?

94
00:07:58,228 --> 00:07:59,687
Uncle Milton's parole.

95
00:07:59,855 --> 00:08:02,439
And it was delicious.
It was, wasn't it, Milton?

96
00:08:02,607 --> 00:08:07,319
When are you getting married?
In early June, in the garden.

97
00:08:07,487 --> 00:08:09,780
Oh...

98
00:08:09,948 --> 00:08:12,867
What about Harold and bees?
I'm allergic to bees.

99
00:08:13,034 --> 00:08:14,743
BARBARA:
We'll spray you.

100
00:08:15,203 --> 00:08:18,914
Cold salmon, a lovely
cucumber salad,
strawberries.

101
00:08:19,082 --> 00:08:24,253
I'm afraid I am allergic to strawberries.

102
00:08:25,422 --> 00:08:27,715
Is this all right with you?

103
00:08:27,883 --> 00:08:34,555
Today, I'm consider myself
the luckiest man-man-man
on the face of the earth-earth-earth.

104
00:08:34,723 --> 00:08:36,599
The Lou Gehrig line from...

105
00:08:36,766 --> 00:08:39,101
Remember, Dad, the Lou Gehrig line from, uh...

106
00:08:39,269 --> 00:08:40,769
Pride of the Yankees.
Pride of the Yankees.

107
00:08:40,937 --> 00:08:42,229
Pride of the Yankees!
Yeah. Yeah.

108
00:08:42,397 --> 00:08:45,691
Baseball. It's baseball.
Historical reference.

109
00:08:45,859 --> 00:08:47,776
I would like to propose a toast.

110
00:08:47,944 --> 00:08:50,613
ALL: Hear, hear.
To my kid sister.

111
00:08:50,780 --> 00:08:53,616
To Walter and my baby.

112
00:08:53,783 --> 00:08:55,951
BARBARA:
To Walter and Annie.

113
00:08:58,121 --> 00:09:01,957
Everyone, please eat before it gets cold.

114
00:09:04,544 --> 00:09:08,672
Here it is. The Historical
Society wanted this

115
00:09:08,840 --> 00:09:10,507
and I never would give it to them.

116
00:09:10,675 --> 00:09:12,718
ANNIE:
Oh, Mum...

117
00:09:12,886 --> 00:09:15,429
BARBARA: I noticed these things
are back in fashion.

118
00:09:15,597 --> 00:09:17,473
ANNIE:
Grandmother's dress.

119
00:09:17,641 --> 00:09:22,102
Oh, honey.
He's a lovely man, Annie.

120
00:09:22,270 --> 00:09:25,898
I know he is wonderful, isn't he?

121
00:09:26,316 --> 00:09:28,817
And he's such a wonderful athlete.
Are his folks nice?

122
00:09:28,985 --> 00:09:30,152
You'll love them.

123
00:09:30,320 --> 00:09:32,863
We're going down
to DC tonight to be with
them Christmas morning.

124
00:09:33,031 --> 00:09:37,034
How did it happen?
It's silly, really.

125
00:09:37,202 --> 00:09:40,204
I mean, I'd seen him at the office.
Obviously I'd seen him.

126
00:09:40,372 --> 00:09:42,373
He's the associate publisher.

127
00:09:42,540 --> 00:09:45,876
And then one day we
both ordered sandwiches
from the same place

128
00:09:46,044 --> 00:09:50,547
and he got my lettuce
and tomato on whole wheat,
which, of course, he was allergic to.

129
00:09:50,715 --> 00:09:52,716
And I got his lettuce and tomato on white.

130
00:09:52,884 --> 00:09:55,177
How amazing.
It is, isn't it?

131
00:09:55,345 --> 00:09:57,346
You make a million decisions that mean nothing

132
00:09:57,514 --> 00:10:00,349
and then one day
you order takeout
that changes your life.

133
00:10:00,517 --> 00:10:02,559
Destiny takes a hand.

134
00:10:02,727 --> 00:10:05,187
Mum, destiny is something we've invented

135
00:10:05,355 --> 00:10:08,983
because we can't stand
the fact that everything
that happens is accidental.

136
00:10:09,150 --> 00:10:12,569
Then how do you explain
that you both ordered exactly
the same sandwich

137
00:10:12,737 --> 00:10:14,446
except for the bread?

138
00:10:14,614 --> 00:10:16,031
How many people in this world

139
00:10:16,199 --> 00:10:20,536
like lettuce and tomato
without something else,
like tuna?

140
00:10:20,704 --> 00:10:25,666
Well, it wasn't a sign.
It was a coincidence.

141
00:10:25,834 --> 00:10:29,795
I was in Atlantic City
with my family,
Cliff was a waiter.

142
00:10:29,963 --> 00:10:34,758
He wasn't even supposed
to work that night.
Suppose he hadn't?

143
00:10:34,926 --> 00:10:38,554
He asked me
to take a midnight walk
on the Steel Pier.

144
00:10:38,722 --> 00:10:42,766
I probably told you this
a million times,
but I don't care.

145
00:10:42,934 --> 00:10:45,519
Then he held my hand.

146
00:10:45,687 --> 00:10:51,150
At one point I looked down
and I couldn't tell which fingers
were his and which were mine.

147
00:10:51,318 --> 00:10:55,154
And I knew.
What?

148
00:10:55,322 --> 00:10:57,406
You know.

149
00:10:57,615 --> 00:11:02,661
What?
Magic. It was magic.

150
00:11:03,830 --> 00:11:05,164
Magic.

151
00:11:05,332 --> 00:11:09,668
I knew we'd be together
forever. And that everything
would be wonderful.

152
00:11:09,836 --> 00:11:12,463
Just the way you feel about Walter.

153
00:11:12,630 --> 00:11:17,009
Walter. It's quite a formal name.

154
00:11:17,761 --> 00:11:21,305
One of the things
I truly knew was that
your father and I

155
00:11:21,473 --> 00:11:23,932
were going to have a wonderful time in

156
00:11:24,100 --> 00:11:26,518
the sack, I believe you call it.

157
00:11:26,686 --> 00:11:27,728
Mum.

158
00:11:27,896 --> 00:11:29,772
Of course it took several
years before everything

159
00:11:29,939 --> 00:11:31,857
worked like clockwork in that department.

160
00:11:32,025 --> 00:11:34,068
So don't be worried if it takes a while.

161
00:11:34,235 --> 00:11:39,365
We already...
Fine, fine. Fiddly-dee. How's it working?

162
00:11:39,532 --> 00:11:44,411
Like clockwork.
Oh, honey...

163
00:11:44,954 --> 00:11:46,413
[ANNIE GASPS]

164
00:11:46,873 --> 00:11:51,001
It's a sign.
You don't believe in signs.

165
00:11:54,672 --> 00:11:56,298
